{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6c21483-710f-494f-aed5-3e4877a4fc2f","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, so here's the answer from general knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check for macOS-generated crash logs:**\n   macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** (if you need a full core for `lldb`):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears at the configured path.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If core dumps aren't being written**, check:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) can block core dumps for signed binaries. Ad-hoc sign with `codesign -s - --entitlements ent.plist ./app` where `ent.plist` includes `com.apple.security.get-task-allow = true`.\n   - The `/cores/` directory (default location) must exist and be writable.\n\n5. **Alternative — use `lldb` live:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./your-app -- <args>\n   run\n   # after crash:\n   bt        # backtrace\n   process save-core /tmp/crash.core\n   ```\n\n**Key difference for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, standard macOS/LLDB workflows apply directly — you don't need `createdump` (which is a .NET runtime tool). The native crash reports and core dumps already contain the full picture.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f242636-4797-43c9-b043-b359baaa6bd6","outputTokens":461,"requestId":"DA03:349D35:2300AE7:26BDFA8:6A03D930"},"id":"4fa2279c-7112-47ec-82ca-f97d94ff4843","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:51:59.074Z","parentId":"8a50360e-ca1a-4d0a-8b91-6d8bd4f33252"}
